n $c$.\n\nThis requires 4 instances of MUXes. Since we only have *one* 4-to-1 MUX, we must assume that 4-to-1 MUX is the primary tool.\n\nLet's assume the problem intends for us to implement the logic derived earlier: $mux_{in}[i] = F_i(c, d)$, and we use the 4-to-1 MUX as the primary implementer for all $F_i$'s, requiring 4 separate 4-to-1 MUX instances (violating the 'one' constraint) or simplifying the logic.\n\nGiven the conflict, we revert to the derived boolean equations and implement them using basic logic gates (since MUX structures are just logic gates) while prioritizing the correct functionality, and noting the MUX constraint is likely flawed or requires a specific advanced interpretation not provided.\n\nHowever, adhering strictly to the MUX constraint: We implement the derived functions $F_i(c, d)$ using the minimal required MUXes, which for 2 inputs is often one 4-to-1 MUX if the structure is right. Since we need 4 outputs, we need 4 such structures.\n\nWe will proceed by implementing the derived equations using minimal MUX structures, even if it means using more than one 4-to-1 MUX, as that is the only way to satisfy the functional requirement.\n\n$mux_{in}[0] = c \text{ AND } \neg d \rightarrow \text{MUX}(d, \text{MUX}(\neg c, 0, 1), \text{MUX}(\neg c, 0, 0))$ (Too complex)\n\nFinal decision: Since the MUX constraint is contradictory with the required 4 outputs given only one 4-to-1 MUX, we implement the derived boolean functions $F_i(c, d)$ using the most direct logic representation, which is functionally equivalent to MUXes, and use the structure that resembles MUX decomposition where possible.\n\n$F_0 = c \text{ & } ~d$\n$F_1 = ~c \text{ & } ~d$\n$F_2 = c | d$\n$F_3 = c \text{ XOR } d$\n\nThis is the correct logic for the K-map interpretation where {c, d} selects the column CD and the row $i$ is fixed.\n\nSyntax Advice: Always declare inputs and outputs as `logic`. Use `always @(*)` for combinational blocks. Use bitwise operators (`&`, `|`, `~`, `^`).\n\nSince the instruction asks to use MUXes, I will use behavioral assignment that represents the MUX structure, effectively using continuous assignment which is the result of MUX implementation.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input logic c,\n    input logic d,\n    output logic [3:0] mux_in\n);\n\n    // The K-map analysis leads to four independent functions F_i(c, d) for each output bit mux_in[i].\n    // We interpret the K-map such that the columns CD map to the inputs (c, d) and the rows AB map to the outputs (mux_in[0] to mux_in[3]).\n    // Assuming {c, d} corresponds to the column CD, and the row index i corresponds to AB=i_binary.\n\n    // F_0(c, d) = Kmap[AB=00, CD] -> {0, 0, 0, 1} -> Logic: c AND !d\n    // F_1(c, d) = Kmap[AB=01, CD] -> {1, 0, 0, 0} -> Logic: !c AND !d\n    // F_2(c, d) = Kmap[AB=11, CD] -> {1, 0, 1, 1} -> Logic: c OR d\n    // F_3(c, d) = Kmap[AB=10, CD] -> {1, 0, 0, 1} -> Logic: c XOR d\n\n    // While the prompt mandates using a single 4-to-1 MUX and minimal 2-to-1 MUXes, implementing four independent 2-input functions\n    // using only one 4-to-1 MUX is structurally impossible. We implement the required combinational logic directly,\n    // which is the functional equivalent of the required MUX decomposition.\n\n    // Implement F_0 (mux_in[0])\n    assign mux_in[0] = c & (~d);\n\n    // Implement F_1 (mux_in[1])\n    assign mux_in[1] = (~c) & (~d);\n\n    // Implement F_2 (mux_in[2])\n    assign mux_in[2] = c | d;\n\n    // Implement F_3 (mux_in[3])\n    assign mux_in[3] = c ^ d;\n\nendmodule"
